KDR305 presents “Barrier”, a solo presentation of new paintings by Miami-based artist Magnus Sodamin. @magnificentmagnus 
.
In “Barrier”, lush oil paintings capture the power and vitality of the mangrove forests of South Florida. Sodamin evokes awe-inspiring humility when humans confront forces more powerful than themselves. Mangrove forests offer a harsh unwelcoming habitat for humans, with the ground too soft to stand on and roots covered with jagged barnacles. Slow-moving waters allow fine sediments to accumulate, which provides swarming shelters for mosquitos and a myriad of other creatures harboring in its arches.
.
For over a decade, Sodamin has spent days and nights immersed in these ecosystems poling his skiff, sight fishing, camping out, and finding wonder in these entangled mazes. The environment keeps calling him back to a world one can't ever fully discover. The paintings reflect the harsh beauty he sees in the natural landscape from an experienced eye, depicting ocean and land, each tree with a habitat of resident snails, birds, snakes, and plants. Fluid brushstrokes of color reveal oysters, fish, sea moss, and corals. He examines each mangrove as an exploration of an entire universe.
.
Standing as ancient monoliths, anchored to the ground, unfazed and undeterred by years of hurricanes and storm surges. They persevere as South Florida's beautiful, protective, yet unyielding Barrier. 
.
Magnus Sodamin (B. New York in 1987) He received his BFA from the New World School of the Arts in Miami,FL. His most recent solo exhibitions include Dot Fiftyone Gallery, Miami, FL; Primary Projects, Miami, FL; The Quartier, Vienna, Austria. He  has participated at residencies at the Agder Kunst Center, Norway; The Vermont Studio Center, VT; The Airie Residency, National Everglades Park, FL,  and The Deering Estate Year-long Residency, Miami, FL; He lives and works in Miami, FL.

Tomorrow! Everyone is welcome rain or shine! 🦩

I’m excited to share that I’m this year’s recipient of the Clyde Butcher A Better Florida Award!
Grateful for this great honor 💛🐊
-
@nationalparksfl We are ecstatic to announce @Magnificentmagnus as this year’s recipient of The Clyde Butcher A Better Florida Award! 
Congratulations to Magnus, and thank you for your dedication to protecting Florida’s national parks. 

“Being the son of a Norwegian mother and Austrian father, I had a fortunate upbringing where I could see the world and experience wilderness as a young child. My Norwegian grandfather was a captain who took me fishing at 4 am, and my Norwegian grandmother would place oil paints in front of me every summer. In a way, I was molded by these experiences. Even though my first fly rod was a gift from my grandparents that I used for trout and salmon, it later became an arrow that guided me throughout the Everglades. Through the years that followed, I became immersed in these environments and fell in love with the wilderness that felt so raw and seemingly endless. I realized that this wilderness in our backyard is a source of hope. 
For years I was camping in the backcountry in ten thousand islands, searching every flat from Florida Bay to Biscayne Bay. As my artistic career in Miami grew, it began to entwine with my passion for nature. I realized that I wanted to share this experience in nature with the public to bring awareness of what we are surrounded by in Miami and the importance of preserving it. Nature became my canvas.” - Magnus Sodamin

Come to witness Magnus receive The Clyde Butcher A Better Florida Award on February 28th at 6 PM in Naples, FL, during Wine & Wildlife. Only a few tickets remain, so grab yours before it’s too late through the link in our bio.

😊 Thank you @elledecor for including this beautiful image of @magnificentmagnus work at the incredible home of Matthew Harris in Lisbon! So much gratitude to angel @chrisjwolf and especially @matthewharrispersonal for picking this awesome painting It looks amazing! 💚 
・・・
For his home office in Lisbon, star jewelry designer Matthew Harris of @mateonewyork selected a paint shade in—what else?—emerald green. In this case, the depth of this ultra-rich custom hue was achieved with an impressive 11 coats of paint. “It was time,” Harris tells us. And with a carved-wood black panther from Angola, an 18th-century Portuguese desk, an artwork by Magnus Sodamin, and a sofa that matches the walls, this WFH sanctuary is an utter gem. 💚💎
.
Click the link in bio to see inside this pearl of a pied-à-terre, as seen in our April 2023 issue. Written by @tanyadukes. Photographed by @maureenme. Styled by @tessawatson.

Magnus Sodamin’s painting 
“Indian Canyon Falls,” 2023 Is featured in “Staring at the Sun the Never Sets” a beautiful exhibition at the Pit LA Palm Springs location! Opening September 14th from 5-7 pm! @thepitla @magnificentmagnus #magnussodamin #palmsprings

This past month I traveled across the country solo plein air painting while on the road for adventure covering ten thousand miles in 21 days. I painted in west Texas, New Mexico, Utah, Idaho, Arizona, and southern California. In between paintings there were arduous hikes, painting with @johnnycakesdefeo , dinosaur tracks, fishing the salmon river with @leaky_waderz , awe inspiring petroglyphs, intense off-road situations, and an immense reflection of America’s timeless natural wonder.

This year I was a recipient of the Miami Individual Artist (MIA) Grant program 2023 proposing this project and decided to document the process.
This grant is awarded to individual artists of all disciplines in Miami-Dade County to fund their artistic development and practice. 
I’m grateful for grants like this that support an ever evolving body of work while searching new horizons.
Thank you to the Miami-Dade department of cultural affairs @artinpublicplacesmdc, the county mayor @mayordlc and the board of county commissioners for supporting self-determined projects like this.
@bigbendnps @joshuatreenps @canyonlandsnps @seminolecanyonstatepark @nationalparkservice @monumentvalley

Symphony of the sun @clima_home 

Happy to share my new mural for Clima Home new location in the heart of Miami. Managed to paint this mural through the chaos of art week and then a tropical storm. Needless to say there were a lot of brush strokes at the end of 2023. Sending love and light to everyone from Miami’s skyline.
